column1: 22837`https://www.cityofchicago.org/dam/city/depts/rev/supp_info/TaxSupportingInformation/March_2006_Info_Bulletin_Boat_Mooring_Tax.pdf`Success`Success`1`1`Not a fillable PDF.`Vol. 9  No. 1                                               CHICAGO DEPARTMENT OF REVENUE  March 2006  INFORMATIONAL BULLETIN  #Chicago Boat Mooring Tax  What is a watercraft?  Watercraft means any boat
column3: or other craft used or capable of being used as a means of transportation on water.  Who is responsible for payment of the tax?  The individual being charged a mooring or docking fee is responsible for payment of the tax to the marina or docking facility.   Who is responsible for collection of the tax?  Effective January 1st
column5: all Chicago mooring and docking facilities are responsible for collecting and remitting the tax to the Department.  The tax must be collected at the time the fee is collected.  Is there a commission granted for collecting and remitting the tax?  Yes
column6: the collector is allowed a commission of 1% of the tax collected and timely remitted to the Department.  To be considered timely
column7: the remittance and return must be physically received or received in an envelope postmarked by the Unites States Postal Service on or before the due date.  Per chapter 3-4 of the Municipal Code
column8: late payments incur interest at a rate of 12% per annum simple interest
column10: based on a 365 day calendar year and a late penalty rate of 5% of the tax due.  How often is the Boat Mooring Tax  remitted and when are returns due?  The tax is to be remitted monthly with taxes collected in one month payable by the last day of the subsequent month.  The tax return for periods commencing on July 1st of each year and ending on June 30 of the subsequent year
column11: is filed annually and is due by August 15th of each year.  Questions?  If you have questions or need more information
column12: please write us.  Our address is:  City of Chicago Department of Revenue Tax Policy Division c/o Raul Medina 333 South State Street
column14: Illinois 60604-3977 rmedina@cityofchicago.org  TO:  All Chicago Marinas and Docking                                   Facilities  The purpose of this informational bulletin is to discuss certain issues pertaining to the Chicago Boat Mooring Tax
column15: Chicago Municipal Code Chapter 3-16.  General Information  The Boat Mooring tax is imposed on the mooring (docking) of any watercraft in a body of water located within the corporate limits of the City of Chicago for a fee.  The tax became effective on January 1st 1984 but has undergone some recent changes.  What is the current tax rate?  The current Boat Mooring tax rate is 7% of the mooring or docking fee.  This rate became effective on January 1st
column16: 2003.  Prior to this date the tax was 25% of the mooring or docking fee.  What is a mooring or docking fee?  Mooring or Docking fee means the consideration paid for the mooring or docking or the right to the mooring or docking of any watercraft
column18: whether received in money or otherwise
column20: but not including any consideration paid for the mooring or docking of a watercraft in the loading or unloading of goods or materials
column21: or the boarding or unboarding of passengers
column22: in the conduct of an interstate transportation business.

column19: I L L I N O I S     6 0 6 1 1         Do you wonder what was happening in 1902? That’s the year the old water main was installed  beneath your street. Among other things:             Animal Crackers were introduced to the American public.    Theodore Roosevelt became the first American President to ride in an automobile.    The first college football bowl game
column20: the Rose Bowl between Michigan and Stanford
column22: California.     JC Penney opened its first store
column26: was formed.    Denmark became the first country to adopt fingerprinting as a way to identify criminals.    Richard J. Daley was born; he served as Mayor of Chicago from 1955 until his death in   1976.        RICHARD J. DALEY                          GEORGE ST.
column27: RIDGEWAY AVE. & LAWNDALE AVE. WATER PROJECT   PROJECT DESCRIPTION     Project:  The Department of Water Management will soon be installing 2
column28: 492 feet of 8-inch  water main in W. George Street
column29: from N. Avers Avenue to N. Ridgeway Avenue
column31: from W. George Street to W. Diversey Avenue
column33: from N.  Hamlin Avenue to N. Milwaukee Avenue.    Reason:  The old main consists of a 6-inch pipe and we want to expand capacity. Further
column34: the old  pipe dates back to 1902 and needs to be replaced.     Timing:  We will begin installing the new water main shortly
column35: and expect the work to be  completed in late June 2014. This includes restoration. Dates may change depending on weather  and other factors. If there is any appreciable change
column36: we will notify you.    Traffic: We will allow traffic to flow on W. George Street
column38: and N.  Lawndale Avenue outside of our working hours.  When we are working in the street
column39: we have to  close it to traffic for reasons of safety. You will always be able to reach your home or business
column40: even if it means putting a metal plate in place.  Outside of working hours
column41: a lane will be left open  for local traffic only.     Parking: We will post our work area for “No Parking” as needed
column42: during work hours (7am- 4pm). We are agreeable to parking outside of those hours
column43: but will have to insist that cars be  moved by the start of the next workday. We will try to preserve as much parking as we can.   CONTACT NUMBERS   24-HOUR SERVICE AND INFORMATION LINE      3-1-1   ALDERMAN ARIEL REBOYRAS   773-794-3095   ASSISTANT WATER MANAGEMENT COMMISSIONER TOM LAPORTE   312-742-1029                                                  FREQUENTLY ASKED QUESTIONS             What if there is a problem?  There are always surprises in any construction project.  If you  have any concerns or questions
column44: you can ask our foreman in the street.  You can also call  Assistant Commissioner Tom LaPorte directly at 312-742-1029.  His cell is on the voicemail  message
column45: in case it’s off hours.    Can I park when you’re not working? We have no problem with you parking outside of our  working hours.  We have to insist that cars be out of our way at the start of the workday.     Will this ever end?  Yes.  As a matter of fact
column46: the job is slated to conclude in late June 2014.  This includes restoration. We always hesitate to promise specific dates
column47: since we are at the mercy  of other factors like weather and emergencies elsewhere in town.    Will you shut my water off? Yes
column48: maybe a couple of times. When we switch over the services  from the old main to the new main
column49: we interrupt service. We give you 24-hour notice when this  is to happen.  In any construction project
column50: there is also a risk that an old pipe will break.  They  can be fragile. This may necessitate an emergency shutdown.  If we do this
column51: we will let you know  what is happening
column52: even though we may be unable to give prior warning.    Why should I be nice about this?  The crew working in the street will work hard to be good  neighbors
column53: and to respect both your convenience and your quality-of-life.  By working together
column54: we can complete this important project as friends working for the improvement of our  community.    After your old water main has been replaced and you have been connected to your new water  main
column55: please open all your water faucets and hose taps and flush your water for 3 to 5 minutes.  Sediment and metals can collect in the aerator screen located at the tip of your faucets. These  screens should be removed prior to flushing. This flushing will help maintain optimum water  quality by removing sediment
column57: or any lead particulates that may have come loose from your  property’s water service line as a result of the water main replacement. If you have any questions  or concerns about your water quality
column58: please call us at 312-744-8190.               DOES YOUR BASEMENT FLOOD?     The Department of Water Management would like to work with you and your neighbors to  reduce the risk of basement flooding.  We are promoting a collective response as the only  strategy—homeowners joining together on a neighborhood basis to work with us on  practical steps (public and private) to protect your property and peace of mind.    Want to learn more?  http://www.cityofchicago.org/watermanagement/bfp             DEPA RTM EN T OF WATER MANAGEM EN T            C ITY  OF CHICAGO    What is MeterSave?    MeterSave is a program to encourage Chicago homeowners to voluntarily install meters to  monitor water usage. Meters allow single family and two-flat homeowners to pay for only the  water actually used
column59: encouraging efforts to save water and money while protecting one of our  most precious natural resources.    Water charges in non-metered homes are tied to factors such as building size
column60: lot-size and  number of plumbing fixtures. Metered homes are billed according to actual use. This means that  with minimal effort
column61: participating homeowners could save money on their water bills.      Homeowner Incentives   Non-metered homeowners participating in MeterSave are eligible for the following:    A 7-year guarantee that the home water bill will be no higher than it would have if the meter   had not been installed. Bill will not exceed the assessed rate for that year.     Choice of one of the following (while supplies last):   rain barrel
column62:     water meter monitor (a refrigerator magnet that shows water usage)    outdoor water conservation kit or      And
column63: two of the above incentives if a whole block volunteers!   indoor water conservation kit      Frequently Asked Questions:   How and when do I sign up?   Interested non-metered single family and two-flat homeowners may visit www.metersave.org
column65: or call 312-744-4H2O. Please have your 12-digit account number ready.  Space is  limited based on funding availability and the number of volunteers.     What will it cost to participate?  The City of Chicago Department of Water Management will install a water meter complete with  the automatic meter reading (AMR) technology in your home FREE of charge.    AMR technology allows readings to be transmitted via wireless radio technology to Water  Management vehicles as they drive by
column66: eliminating the need for readings to take place inside the  home.  Bills will be issued bi-monthly and reflect only the actual amount of water used.     Do I have to be current on my water bill?  Yes.  Homeowners must be current on payment plan and water bill to participate in this limited  time offer of a 7-year guarantee.    For payment plan information call 312-744-4H20 (4426).      1 0 0 0   E A S T   O H I O   S T R E E T
column67: C H I C A G O
column68: I L L I N O I S     6 0 6 1 1           When can I have a meter installed?  Online meter installation scheduling is available at www.metersave.org  Otherwise
column69: Water  Management will contact you to schedule a time for meter installation.      Small changes made by Chicagoans can have a tremendous impact on the sustainability of  our water supply
column70: such as:     Turn off the faucet while brushing your teeth or shaving.  This can save over 500 gallons  per month per person.    Install high-efficiency
column71: low-flow toilets.  Toilets alone consume 26% of household water  consumption.  A leaky toilet wastes 200 gallons of water per day.    Install high-efficiency washing machines. This can save energy and water consumption.    Fill the sink with dishwater instead of washing dishes with an open tap.  This saves 25  gallons per wash.    If you own a dishwasher
column72: wait until you have a full load to run it.  Dishwashers typically  use half the energy
column74: and less soap than washing dishes in the sink.    Garden with plants that are native to Chicago.  This can reduce outdoor water use by 20- 50%.    Use rain barrels to capture rainwater for watering lawns and gardens.    Use a timer or a rain sensor to monitor lawn irrigation: Sprinkler systems use thousands  of gallons of water per cycle.  Installing a timer or rain sensor will save money and water by  preventing needless watering.         WATER   Our Most Precious Resource   Lake Michigan has lost almost 32 trillion gallons of water--the equivalent of over 45 million  Olympic-sized swimming pools of water-- over the past decade. Our region could face severe  water shortages by 2050 if we fail to take decisive action.     More than half of water consumption in Chicago occurs within homes.   Over 5.4 million people-- 44% of the population of the State of Illinois
column75: depend on the Chicago  Department of Water Management to provide a reliable supply of drinking water from Lake  Michigan.     Volunteer for a meter today to save water and money!           Please go to www.metersave.org     By phone call 3-1-1

column1: 25667`https://www.cityofchicago.org/content/dam/city/depts/dhr/supp_info/JobSpecifications/JobSpecName/AUTOMOTIVE-PAINTER_4605.pdf`Success`Success`2`2`Not a fillable PDF.`Code:  4605  Operation and Construction Service  Building Maintenance and Operation Group  Painting Trades Series                                  CLASS TITLE: Automotive Painter    CHARACTERISTICS OF THE CLASS:  Under supervision
column2: performs journey  level work in the preparation and painting of automobiles and other  motor vehicles; and performs related duties as required.    ESSENTIAL DUTIES:  Reads specifications and work orders to assess work  required and to determine the most appropriate preparation and  application methods to use; ensures adequate supplies of tools
column3: equipment and materials are at work sites to complete jobs; operates  power equipment to sand and remove paint and rust spots from vehicles;  fills small dents and scratches with body filler; cleans and prepares  surfaces to ensure paint and other finishes will adhere properly;  removes or masks parts of vehicle surfaces not to be painted such as  chrome trim
column5: windows and mirrors; mixes and blends paints  to match the original color of vehicles; uses spray guns to apply  successive coats of paint such as primer
column6: lacquer and enamel to  vehicles; checks quality of work on refinished vehicles to ensure  appropriate consistency and color; affixes decals and stencils  letters
column8: insignias and other identification marks onto  vehicle surfaces; prepares work activity reports.     RELATED DUTIES:  Cleans paint applicators
column9: equipment and work site  after paint job is completed; may prepare cost estimates of materials  and man hours needed to complete automotive paint jobs.       MINIMUM QUALIFICATIONS:    Training and Experience.  Successful completion of a US Department of  Labor registered automotive painting apprenticeship training program  and journeyman status
column10: or an equivalent combination of training and  experience.    A valid State of Illinois driver’s license is required.      Knowledge
column11: Abilities and Skill.  Good knowledge of the work methods  and techniques used in mixing and applying the different types of  paints used in automotive painting.  Good knowledge of paint products  and equipment used in automotive painting.  Good knowledge of safety  practices and procedures.    Physical ability to use spray guns to apply paint and finishes to  vehicles.  Ability to mix paints to achieve a good match with original  paint.  Ability to work safely.  Ability to prepare work activity       Code:  4605  Operation and Construction Service  Building Maintenance and Operation Group  Painting Trades Series       CLASS TITLE:  Automotive Painter    (Cont'd)    reports.     Skill in the mixing and application of different types of paint.    Skill in the use of tools and equipment used in automotive painting.    Basic math skills.  Basic oral and written communication skills.    Physical Requirements.  Ability to lift and carry tools and materials   weighing up to 35 pounds frequently and greater than 35 pounds  occasionally.     Working Conditions.  Unavoidable exposure to paint fumes.  Work is  performed in spray booths or special ventilation booths.    Equipment.  Standard tools and equipment of the trade including paint  spray guns.  Safety equipment including respirators and masks.            NOTE: While the list of essential duties is intended to be as inclusive   as possible
column12: there may be other duties which are essential  to particular positions within the class.                        November
